### Spring Profiles

Profiles provide a way to segregate parts of application configuration for different environments (dev, test, prod).

### Profile-Specific Properties

Name property files as `application-{profile}.properties`:

```
application-dev.properties   # Development settings
application-test.properties  # Test settings
application-prod.properties  # Production settings
application.properties       # Shared defaults
```

### Activating Profiles

```bash
# Command line
java -jar app.jar --spring.profiles.active=prod

# Environment variable
set SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=dev

# application.properties
spring.profiles.active=dev
```

### @Profile Annotation

Conditionally enable beans based on active profiles.

```java
@Service
@Profile("dev")
public class DevDataSourceInitializer {
    // Only loaded in dev profile
}

@Service
@Profile("!dev")
public class ProductionService {
    // Loaded in all profiles except dev
}

@Service
@Profile({"test", "dev"})
public class TestDataLoader {
    // Loaded in test and dev profiles
}
```

### Profile Groups

```yaml
spring:
  profiles:
    group:
      dev: [dev, local-logging]
      staging: [staging, debug-logging]
      prod: [prod, minimal-logging]
```

### Programmatic Profile Check

```java
@Autowired
private Environment env;

public boolean isDevProfile() {
    return Arrays.asList(env.getActiveProfiles()).contains("dev");
}
```
